ddlesex, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1430–Abt 1499":"1430–circa 1499","1430–1499":"1430–1499","1432–Male":"1432–Overleden","1425–1467":"1425–1467","1454–1482":"1454–1482","1410–Male":"1410–Overleden","1405–Female":"1405–Overleden","19 June 1467":"19 juni 1467","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Abt 1499":"circa 1499","1425":"1425","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1499":"1499","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1430":"1430","1405":"1405","London, City of London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Middlesex, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1430–Abt 1499":"1430–about 1499","1430–1499":"1430–1499","1432–Male":"1432–Deceased","1425–1467":"1425–1467","1454–1482":"1454–1482","1410–Male":"1410–Deceased","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","19 June 1467":"19 June 1467","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Abt 1499":"about 1499","1425":"1425","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1499":"1499","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1430":"1430","1405":"1405","London, City of London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Middlesex, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Radcliffe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Ratliff  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ratliff","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from one or more of the places so named, such as Radcliffe (Lancashire), Radcliffe on Trent and Ratcliffe on Soar (both Nottinghamshire), Radclive (Buckinghamshire), Ratcliffe Culey and Ratcliffe on the Wreake (both Leicestershire), Ratclyffe in Clyst Hydon, Ratcliffes in Thorverton, and Ratcliffes in Broad Clyst (all Devon), Ratcliff in Stepney (Middlesex), and Rackley in Compton Bishop (Somerset). The placenames derive from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + <i>clif</i> ‘cliff, bank, steep slope’ (see also   Rutley  ). A family of the name <i>Radcliffe</i> trace their descent from Sir Nicholas <i>de Radclyffe</i>. He is said to have been a knight who held the major of Radcliffe in Lancashire and served Roger de Poitou, Baron de Marsey in the 11th century."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Radcliffe was born in 1430, in London, Middlesex, England, her father, William de Radcliffe III, was 21 and her mother, Jane Mansell, was 25. She married Henry Bryce in 1450, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1499, in her hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1430–Abt 1499":"1430–umbes 1499","1430–1499":"1430–1499","1432–Male":"1432–Surnud","1425–1467":"1425–1467","1454–1482":"1454–1482","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","19 June 1467":"19. juuni 1467","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Abt 1499":"umbes 1499","1425":"1425","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1499":"1499","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1430":"1430","1405":"1405","London, City of London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Middlesex, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1430–Abt 1499":"1430–noin 1499","1430–1499":"1430–1499","1432–Male":"1432–Kuollut","1425–1467":"1425–1467","1454–1482":"1454–1482","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","19 June 1467":"19. kesäkuuta 1467","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Abt 1499":"noin 1499","1425":"1425","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1499":"1499","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1430":"1430","1405":"1405","London, City of London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Middlesex, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1430–Abt 1499":"1430–environ 1499","1430–1499":"1430–1499","1432–Male":"1432–Décédé","1425–1467":"1425–1467","1454–1482":"1454–1482","1410–Male":"1410–Décédé","1405–Female":"